		{"id":"0c5d8b66bfcea773","type":"text","text":"# Things to do\n\n| Module                                     |    Type    |    To Submit | Due Date   | Completed |\n| :----------------------------------------- | :--------: | -----------: | ---------- | --------- |\n| <span style=\"color: red\">AIAB</span>       | Coursework | Presentation | 30/04/2026 | No        |\n| <span style=\"color: red\">AIAB</span>       | Coursework |    Portfolio | 19/05/2026 | No        |\n| <span style=\"color: green\">AML</span>      | Coursework |       Report | 21/05/2026 | No        |\n| <span style=\"color: yellow\">SoftEng</span> | Coursework |    Portfolio | 01/05/2026 | No        |\n| <span style=\"color: yellow\">SoftEng</span> |    Exam    |          CBX | 11/05/2026 | No        |\n| <span style=\"color: pink\">DPHC</span>      | Coursework |         Test | 13/03/2026 | Yes       |\n| <span style=\"color: pink\">DPHC</span>      |    Exam    |          CBX | 19/05/2026 | No        |\n\n","x":-1380,"y":-1500,"width":680,"height":340},
		{"id":"052b9f749fd28f1b","type":"text","text":"# 1) Finish GA Pipeline\n\n## a) Check if GenerationController is finished and ready to be used.\nIncludes:\n- Finish refactoring. Check if all function members are fully implemented without bugs.\n\n## b) Check if RobotController is ready\nIncludes:\n- Checking if telemetry data logging works.\n\n## c) Check if NeuralNetwork is ready\nIncludes:\n- Check for potential optimisation chances.\n- Investigate CUDA for calculating on GPU? May make simulation less burdensome on CPU.","x":-1380,"y":-740,"width":680,"height":600,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"3c8c3baafaa4787d","type":"text","text":"# <span style=\"color: red\">AIAB</span>\n\n| To do                                                                | Current Stage |\n| :------------------------------------------------------------------- | :-----------: |\n| 1) Finish GA pipeline                                                |  In progress  |\n| 2) See if testing genotypes with WeBot vs. Gymnasium would be better |  Not started  |\n| 3) Begin training.                                                   |  Not started  |\n| 4) Begin readings for report                                         |  Not started  |\n| 5) Begin writing report.                                             |  Not started  |\n| 6) Begin planning presentation                                       |  Not started  |\n","x":-1380,"y":-1100,"width":680,"height":320,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"c0e3b148779aab72","type":"text","text":"# <span style=\"color: green\">AML</span>\n\n| To do                                                                                     | Current Stage |\n| :---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | :-----------: |\n| 1) Improve spam filter stage by altering k-means clustering                               |  In progress  |\n| 2) Classify document as spam or not spam with naive bayes classifier                      |   Complete    |\n| 3) Classify document as spam or not spam with logistic regression                         |  Not started  |\n| 4) Compare between naive bayes classifer and logistic regression for spam detection       |  Not started  |\n| 5) Classify document as good or bad review using naive bayes classifier                   |   Complete    |\n| 6) Classify document as good or bad review using logistic regression                      |  Not started  |\n| 7) Compare between naive bayes classifer and logistic regression for movie classification |  Not started  |\n\n","x":-320,"y":-1100,"width":680,"height":400,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"57e041d338e5866f","type":"text","text":"# <span style=\"color: yellow\">SoftEng</span>\n\n## 1) Clue to-do list\n\n| To do                                                               | Current Stage |\n| :------------------------------------------------------------------ | :-----------: |\n| 1) Figure out what structure and approach to adopt for unit testing |  Not started  |\n| 2) Write unit tests for everybody's code                            |  Not started  |\n| 3) Identify errors in people's code and inform them                 |  Not started  |\n| 4) Create error testing documentation                               |  Not started  |\n|                                                                     |               |\n## 2) Exam to-do list\n| To do                                    | Current Stage |\n| :--------------------------------------- | :-----------: |\n| 1) Merge all lectures into one large pdf |  Not started  |\n| 2) Begin to revise                       |  Not started  |\n","x":660,"y":-1100,"width":680,"height":520,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"b5840ebe52363099","type":"text","text":"# 2) Check WeBots vs Gymnasium for Training\nInvestigate if WeBots can be remotely controlled by a program. If it cannot be, look into using Gymasium for training and WeBots for visualisation.","x":-1380,"y":-100,"width":680,"height":160,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"c27077d78702a544","type":"text","text":"# 3) Begin Training\nTraining details:\n- 16 genotypes per epoch.\n- GA will use tournament selection\n- Continue GA process until slope of chord fitness rate begins to plateau OR 1000 generations passed?","x":-1380,"y":100,"width":680,"height":220,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"ca6d3aa717cdbcf3","type":"text","text":"# 1) Improve spam filter by altering k-means clustering\nCurrent method assumes labels known. Spam documents in training data HAVE no label.\n\nNew approach: use mean distance of documents to centroid in a cluster.\n- Let $\\bar{d_j}$ denote the average distance of documents to cluster j's centroid.\n\nIdea:\n- As $\\bar{d}_j \\rightarrow \\infty$, cluster becomes more noisy: indicates this is the spam cluster.\n- As $\\bar{d}_j \\rightarrow 0$, cluster becomes less noisy: indicating a coherent cluster which a label that mostly applies to cluster members.\n- The cluster with the greatest $\\bar{d}$ is the cluster containing spam. Any documents with the label associated with this cluster should be filtered out.\n","x":-320,"y":-660,"width":680,"height":400,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"c2196bc61a4cc854","type":"text","text":"# 1.1) Figure out what structure and approach to adopt for unit testing\n\n## Unit Test Structure\nEach unit test is used to verify that ONE thing, such as a function, works as intended.\n\nYou have...\n- Expected output (known by programmer from expected behaviour of the function)\n- Actual output: the output of the function being tested.\n\nThe unit test will return a true or false depending on if expected output is equal to actual output.\n\n## What to test for\nUnit tests should test...\n1) Edge Cases and Boundaries\n2) Invalid inputs\n3) Object State changes\n### Edge Cases and Boundaries\n1) Empty inputs: empty strings, empty lists, zero numeric values.\n2) Minimum and maximum valid values.\n3) Single-element collections.\n4) Very large inputs.\n5) Inputs right at the boundary of what is a valid input.\n\n### Invalid Inputs\nTesting invalid inputs tests whether a function fails in the right way instead of just failing.\n\nThe following counts as invalid input:\n1) Values outside of an allowed range.\n2) String in the wrong format.\n3) Null or undefined values when a value should not be either.\n4) Empty collections when function requires at least one item.\n5) Data of the wrong type.\n6) Combination of values that are individually valid but invalid together.\n\nFunctions should...\n- Throw an exception upon encountering invalid input to prevent program performing undefined behaviour or crashing during runtime.\n- Give a useful error message.\n- Not fail silently. If something goes wrong, it should be reported.\n","x":660,"y":-540,"width":680,"height":960,"color":"3"},
